pr_review_comment_body:
Sorry, but these loops are still freaking me out.  I think you should be able to use this instead:

```
auto descriptors = net(face_chips,16);
auto next = descriptors.begin();
for (auto& img : face_descriptors)
{
    for (auto& face : img)
        face = matrix_cast<double>(*next++);
}
```

Does that work or am I missing something?  All you need to do is initialize face_descriptors appropriately.

You're right, in this case it will not work. What do you suggest in this case since we can have a situation like this:
```
{
    "created_at": ... ,
    "content": {
        "created_at": "......."
    }
}
```
Should the remove_fields parameter perhaps be a list if we would want to separate these cases? In this example if you wanted to delete the non-nested created_at you could just pass 'created_at' or ['created_at'] and for the nested ['content', 'created_at'].

The second option would be to globally remove the given field, so if 'created_at' is given as the parameter, it should remove every appearance of it (including nested).

`ivybridge` sounds like a good compromise. 

https://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gcc/x86-Options.html 

@szha does that look ok, thanks.

> When will output_shape='auto' fail?

for example, this will give a `NotImplementedError`:

    W = theano.shared(np.zeros((1, 1, 3, 3)).astype('float32'))
    def f(X):
        return T.nnet.conv2d(X, W)
    l2 = ExpressionLayer(l, f, output_shape='auto')

`psf` objects aren't guaranteed to have a `sigma` - gaussians do, but certainly many other types of psfs won't (e.g. empirical psfs).  I suggest something like this:
```

if hasattr(self.psf, 'fwhm'):
    self.aperture_radius = self.psf.fwhm
elif hasattr(self.psf, 'sigma'):
    self.aperture_radius = self.psf.sigma.value*gaussian_sigma_to_fwhm
else:
    raise ValueError('PSF does not have sigma or fwhm, so cannot guess the width for aperture photometry')
```

The `simplelayout.js` is a generated file. The original function is in `Block.js`.
@bierik recommended this structure. I think it makes sense. `Block.js` for the implementation and `main.js` for the integration.
It is also way easier to test this way.

`.attr` should not be on the next line, also there are too many calls under `try`. You should use

    try:
        stashref = git.Repository(git_directory(self.directory)).lookup_reference('refs/stash')
    except KeyError:
        return None
    return sum(1 for _ in stashref.log())

Thinking about this now, it makes sense, I think to disallow:
```rust
match path_glob {
  glob @ PathGlob::Wildcard { canonical_dir, symbolic_path, wildcard } => {
    path_glob
  }
}
```

Because you're moving `path_glob` into the destructured `canonical_dir`, `symbolic_path`, and `wildcard`, but then trying to move it again into the result of the expression -- there needs to be a clone happening somewhere. However if we were to match on `&path_glob` (which I just tried), it seems like it's impossible to move something while borrowing it, even if the move happens at the end of the borrowed scope. That seems like it doesn't need to happen? I'm not sure if my analysis is correct.

```
createFilter(value) {
  return value && config.tags.MIN_LENGTH <= value.length <= config.tags.MAX_LENGTH;
```

To do that (and I think it's better from a logic point of view), other functions in the contract should also change. In `close()` function of the same contract it has the same kind of logic:

```
    /// @param first_encoded the last transfer of the first participant
    /// @param second_encoded the last transfer of the second participant
```

And there it does not matter whose the transaction is, first and second transfers can be given in any order.

this is very minor, but I've been trying to enforce a whitespace convention with promises where all function parameters are indented consistently, like this: https://github.com/learningequality/kolibri/blob/develop/kolibri/plugins/learn/assets/src/actions.js#L112

e.g.:

```javascript
  savedUserModel.save(changedValues).then(
    userWithAttrs => {
      // dispatch changes to store
      coreActions.getCurrentSession(store);
      store.dispatch('SET_PROFILE_SUCCESS', true);
      store.dispatch('SET_PROFILE_BUSY', false);
      store.dispatch('SET_PROFILE_EROR', false, '');
    },
    // error handling
    error => {
      // copying logic from user-create-modal
      function errorMessage(apiError) {
        if (apiError.status.code === 400) {
          // access the first apiError message
          return Object.values(apiError.entity)[0][0];
        } else if (apiError.status.code === 403) {
          return apiError.entity[0];
        }
        return '';
      }
      store.dispatch('SET_PROFILE_SUCCESS', false);
      store.dispatch('SET_PROFILE_EROR', true, errorMessage(error));
      store.dispatch('SET_PROFILE_BUSY', false);
    }
  );
}
```
